The '''Czech Social Democratic Party''' ({{lang-cs|<U+010C>esk<U+00E1> strana soci<U+00E1>ln<U+011B> demokratick<U+00E1>}}, <U+010C>SSD) is a [[Social democracy|social-democratic]] [[List of political parties in the Czech Republic|political party]] in the [[Czech Republic]].

==History==
{{Unreferenced section|date=May 2010}}
The '''Social Democratic Czechoslavonic party in Austria''' ({{lang-cs|Soci<U+00E1>ln<U+011B> Demokratick<U+00E1> strana <U+010C>eskoslovansk<U+00E1> v Rakousku}}) was founded on 7 April 1878 in [[Austria-Hungary]] representing the [[Kingdom of Bohemia]] in the Austrian parliament. Its role in the political life of the empire was one of the factors that lead to the creation of independent Czechoslovak Republic. After the collapse of Austria-Hungary, the party became one of the leading parties of the [[first Czechoslovak Republic]].

During the occupation of Czechoslovakia by the Nazi Germany, the party was officially abolished, but its members organised resistance movements illegally within the [[Protectorate of Bohemia and Moravia]] and abroad. After the re-establishment of the [[History of Czechoslovakia (1945-1948)|Czechoslovak Republic]] in 1945, the party returned to its pre-existing structure and became a member of the [[National Front (Czechoslovakia)|National Front]]. In 1948, after the [[Communist Party of Czechoslovakia|Communist Party]] assumed the parliamentary majority, the Czech Social Democratic Party was abolished along with all other non-communist parties. Under the [[Prague Spring|reformist environment in 1968]], there were talks about allowing the recreation of a Social Democratic party, but the Soviet occupation has put an end to such ideas. It was only after the [[Velvet Revolution]] in 1989, when the party was recreated. Since the [[dissolution of Czechoslovakia]], <U+010C>SSD has been one of the major political parties in the Czech Republic.

After the [[Czech legislative election, 1998|1998 parliamentary election]], the party won the most seats, but failed to form a coalition government.  As a result, the party formed a minority government under party leader [[Milo<U+0161> Zeman]].  With only 74 seats out of 200, the government had the [[confidence and supply]] from the [[Civic Democratic Party (Czech Republic)|Civic Democratic Party]] (ODS), under the so-called [[Opposition Agreement]].

The party won the [[Czech legislative election, 2002|elections of 2002]] with 70 of 200 representatives in the [[Chamber of Deputies of the Czech Republic]]. Its chairman [[Vladim<U+00ED>r <U+0160>pidla]] became the [[List of Prime Ministers of the Czech Republic|prime minister]] heading a coalition with two small centre-right parties, the [[Christian and Democratic Union <U+2013> Czechoslovak People's Party|Christian and Democratic Union]] (KDU<U+2013><U+010C>SL) and the [[Freedom Union <U+2013> Democratic Union]] (US-DEU) until his resignation in 2004.

The current chairman of the party is [[Ji<U+0159><U+00ED> Paroubek]] since 2006. His predecessor was [[Stanislav Gross]] from 26 June 2004 to 26 April 2005. Gross resigned after a scandal which arose due to his inability to explain the source of financial resources used to pay for his home. Gross's predecessor [[Vladim<U+00ED>r <U+0160>pidla]] was forced to resign in 2004 after the <U+010C>SSD lost in the [[European Parliament election, 2004 (Czech Republic)|2004 European Parliamentary elections]].

In the [[Czech legislative election, 2006|June 2 and 3, 2006 elections]], the party won 32.3% of the vote and 74 out of 200 seats. The election at first caused a [[stalemate]] since the centre-right parties (with [[Green Party (Czech Republic)|Green Party]]) and centre-left parties each had 100 seats. The stalemate was broken when two <U+010C>SSD deputies, [[Milo<U+0161> Mel<U+010D><U+00E1>k]] and [[Michal Pohanka]] abstained during a [[vote of confidence]], allowing a coalition of the [[Civic Democratic Party (Czech Republic)|Civic Democrats]] (ODS), the KDU-<U+010C>SL, and the Green Party to form a government. Hence the <U+010C>SSD went into opposition.

Following the [[Czech legislative election, 2010|2010 legislative elections]], the <U+010C>SSD gained 22.08% of the vote and became the largest party with 56 seats, but having failed to form a governing coalition, remained in opposition to a coalition of the ODS, conservative [[TOP 09]] and conservative-liberal [[Public Affairs (political party)|Public Affairs]] parties.

=== Overview ===
{{Prose|date=July 2010}}
[[Czech lands]] as part of [[Austria-Hungary]]:
*1878<U+2013>1893 The ''Czechoslavonic Social Democratic Party in Austria'' (''Soci<U+00E1>ln<U+011B>-demokratick<U+00E1> strana <U+010D>eskoslovansk<U+00E1> v Rakousku'') <U+2013> part of [[Social Democratic Party of Austria]]
*1893<U+2013>1918 The ''Czechoslavonic Social Democratic Workers' Party'' (''<U+010C>eskoslovansk<U+00E1> soci<U+00E1>ln<U+011B> demokratick<U+00E1> stranu d<U+011B>lnick<U+00E1>'') <U+2013> independent party
[[Czechoslovakia]]:
*1918<U+2013>1938 The ''Czechoslovak Social Democratic Worker's Party'' (''<U+010C>eskoslovensk<U+00E1> soci<U+00E1>ln<U+011B> demokratick<U+00E1> strana d<U+011B>lnick<U+00E1>'') <U+2013> merged with [[Social Democratic Party of Slovakia|Slovak Social Democrats]]. The party was a member of the [[Labour and Socialist International]] between 1923 and 1938.<ref>Kowalski, Werner. ''Geschichte der sozialistischen Arbeiter-Internationale: 1923 <U+2013> 1938, Berlin: Dt. Verl. d. Wissenschaften, 1985. p. 327.</ref> After the splitup of Austria-Hungary, the [[Czechoslovak Social Democratic Workers Party in the Republic of Austria]] split from the main party.
*1938<U+2013>1941 The ''National Labor Party'' (''N<U+00E1>rodn<U+00ED> strana pr<U+00E1>ce'') <U+2013> united left party of Social Democrats and part of [[Czech National Social Party]]
*1945<U+2013>1948 ''Czechoslovak Social Democracy'' (''<U+010C>eskoslovensk<U+00E1> soci<U+00E1>ln<U+00ED> demokracie'')
*1948<U+2013>1989 <U+2013> merged with the [[Communist Party of Czechoslovakia]], concurrently existed as an exile party with its headquarters in London
*1990<U+2013>1993 ''Czechoslovak Social Democracy'' (''<U+010C>eskoslovensk<U+00E1> soci<U+00E1>ln<U+00ED> demokracie'')
[[Czech Republic]]:
*since 1993 Czech Social Democratic Party (''<U+010C>esk<U+00E1> strana soci<U+00E1>ln<U+011B> demokratick<U+00E1>'')

